The paper deals with network security monitoring and anonymization techniques, which are closely related to the fields of computer security (cs.CR) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The use of multiple anonymized views and the computational cost trade-off suggest a possible connection to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and databases (cs.DB). Finally, the experimental evaluation and comparison of different anonymization techniques may involve machine learning (cs.LG) methods.
